## Three petty crimes in `src/petty.ts`

### 1. `describeCheckout` — Option Bag Junk Drawer (crime_00031, L10–19)

The function takes an unnamed `options` object and pulls six unrelated fields out of it: `currency`, `plan`, `region`, `retry`, `role`, `status`. There's no type, no destructuring at the signature, so the contract lives only in the function body.

**What an agent gets wrong today:** Nothing at the call site says which fields are required, which are optional, or what types they should be. An agent adding a seventh field (`coupon`, say) won't update callers because the signature didn't change. An agent renaming `region` → `country` won't see the existing callers either — TypeScript can't help, because `options` is structurally anything.

**Refactor:** name the shape and destructure at the signature so the contract is local to the function.

```ts
type CheckoutDescriptor = {
  currency: Currency;
  plan: PlanId;
  region: Region;
  role: Role;
  status: CheckoutStatus;
  retry?: RetryPolicy;
};

export function describeCheckout({
  currency, plan, region, role, status, retry,
}: CheckoutDescriptor): string { … }
```

---

### 2. `resolvePaymentResult` — Return Shape Roulette (crime_00032, L21–32)

Three object-literal returns, 0% key overlap, no explicit return type. The detector caught `{ code, message, ok }` vs `{ permanent, url }` as the worst pair.

**What an agent gets wrong today:** TypeScript infers a union, but the union is invisible without hovering. Callers naturally reach for `result.ok` and get `undefined` (falsy) on the redirect branch — silently taking the wrong path without an error. An agent adding a fourth branch with yet another shape compounds the trap; an agent reading the function might "fix" a branch by aligning its keys to a different branch and break the discriminator entirely.

**Refactor:** make the return a discriminated union with an explicit `kind` tag and an explicit return type, so callers are forced to narrow.

```ts
type PaymentResult =
  | { kind: 'ok'; code: string; message: string }
  | { kind: 'redirect'; permanent: boolean; url: string }
  | { kind: 'failed'; reason: string };

function resolvePaymentResult(…): PaymentResult {
  if (…) return { kind: 'ok',       code, message };
  if (…) return { kind: 'redirect', permanent, url };
  return       { kind: 'failed',   reason };
}
```

---

### 3. Negative Flag Maze (crime_00033, L35) + boolean naming drift (crime_00029, L34)

The condition is `!disableBilling && !skipRetry`. Two negative-named booleans, each negated again at the predicate — a double negative on each axis. The boolean-naming-drift finding on the same line is the root cause: the names themselves are inverted.

**What an agent gets wrong today:** Reading "not disable" as "enable" requires a mental flip per flag. An agent extending this with a third flag — `noEmail`, say — will copy the pattern and write `!disableBilling && !skipRetry && !noEmail`. Any single inversion mistake silently flips who gets charged, who gets retried, who gets the receipt. Worse: an agent shortening the condition by introducing `const skipAll = disableBilling || skipRetry; if (!skipAll) …` looks fine in isolation but inverts the meaning if anyone later adds a positive flag to the disjunction.

**Refactor:** flip the names at the source, prefer positive predicates, and pull the combined rule into a named helper before extending it.

```ts
// At the call boundary, take positive flags:
function chargeCustomer({ billing = true, retry = true }: ChargeOptions) {
  const shouldChargeWithRetry = billing && retry;
  if (shouldChargeWithRetry) { … }
}
```

If the callers really must keep `disableBilling`/`skipRetry` for back-compat at an outer layer, invert them once at the entry point and never let the negative names reach the predicate:

```ts
const billingEnabled = !disableBilling;
const retryEnabled   = !skipRetry;
const shouldChargeWithRetry = billingEnabled && retryEnabled;
```

The common thread across all three: each crime makes the **contract invisible at the signature or call site**, which is exactly the surface an agent reads when extending the code.
